\" |<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bizasialive.com/big-zee-entertainment-awards-nominations-list/|title=Big ZEE Entertainment Awards: Nominations list|date=2017-07-22|work=BizAsia {{!}} Media, Entertainment, Showbiz, Events and Music|access-date=2018-03-31|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bollywoodlife.com/news-gossip/big-zee-entertainment-awards-2017-winners-list-alia-bhatt-shahid-kapoor-aishwarya-rai-bachchan-sushant-singh-rajput-are-the-big-winners-of-the-night/|title=Big Zee Entertainment Awards 2017 winners list: Alia Bhatt, Shahid Kapoor, Aishwarya Rai Bachchan, Sushant Singh Rajput are the big winners of the night|last=Banerjee|first=Urmimala|access-date=2018-03-31|language=en-US}}</ref>\n|-\n|Most Entertaining Actor in a Social Film \u2013 Female\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Alia Bhatt\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|Most Entertaining Actor (Film) \u2013 Female\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|Most Entertaining Actor (Film) \u2013 Male\n|Shahid Kapoor\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|Most Entertaining Actor (Film) Debut \u2013 Male\n|Diljit Dosanjh\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|Most Entertaining Music\n|Amit Trivedi\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|Most Entertaining Singer (Female)\n|Kanika Kapoor <small>(for the song \"Da Da Dasse\")</small>\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|[[B4U Movies|B4U]] Viewers Choice Awards\n|2017\n|Best Actress\n| Kareena Kapoor\n|{{Won}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" |\n|-\n|}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Udta Punjab}}\n*{{IMDb title|4434004}}\n*{{Rotten Tomatoes|udta_punjab}}\n{{Balaji Telefilms}}\n{{Anurag Kashyap}}\n\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:2010s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:2010s crime drama films]]\n[[Category:Indian black comedy films]]\n[[Category:Indian crime drama films]]\n[[Category:Indian crime action films]]\n[[Category:Indian crime comedy films]]\n[[Category:Films about drugs]]\n[[Category:Films about cocaine]]\n[[Category:Films about prostitution in India]]\n[[Category:Films about heroin addiction]]\n[[Category:Films about the illegal drug trade]]\n[[Category:Films about organised crime in India]]\n[[Category:Films set in Punjab, India]]\n[[Category:Balaji Motion Pictures films]]\n", "name_user": "122.167.71.94", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Udta_Punjab"}
{"title_page": "Iceland\u2013Israel relations", "text_new": "{{Short description|1=Diplomatic relations between the Republic of Iceland and the State of Israel}}\n{{Infobox Bilateral relations|Iceland-Israel|Iceland|Israel}}\n\n'''Iceland\u2013Israel relations''' refers to the [[diplomatic relations]] between [[Iceland]] and [[Israel]]. Both nations are members of the [[OECD|Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development]] and the [[World Trade Organization]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:Bjarni Benediktsson and Levi Eshkol 1964.jpg|thumb|right|Israeli Prime Minister [[Levi Eshkol]] greeting Icelandic Prime Minister [[Bjarni Benediktsson (born 1908)|Bjarni Benediktsson]] in [[Jerusalem]], 1964.]]\n\n=== Early relations ===\nOne of the first contacts between Iceland and the people of Israel took place in the 1400s when Icelanders (then part of [[Denmark]]) partook in the [[Crusades]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=6mWY_r7C2VsC&pg=PA165&lpg=PA165&dq=Iceland+crusade+in+holy+land&source=bl&ots=eAVq1Nsu68&sig=8Bpb6CHReiTXaYb6px0li1nEUNM&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjVkYjRnL_YAhUI02MKHW-bB-UQ6AEIQTAG#v=onepage&q=Iceland%20crusade%20in%20holy%20land&f=false Denmark and the Crusades: 1400 - 1650]</ref> The first official relations between modern Iceland and Israel took place on 29 November 1947 when Iceland voted in favor for the [[United Nations Partition Plan for Palestine|Partition of Palestine]] which led to the creation of the State of Israel. In May 1948 Iceland recognized the State of Israel and established diplomatic relations.<ref>[http://mfa.gov.il/MFA/AboutTheMinistry/Pages/Israel-s%20Diplomatic%20Missions%20Abroad.aspx Israel's Diplomatic Missions Abroad: Status of relations]</ref>\n\nIn September 1962, Israeli Prime Minister [[David Ben-Gurion]] traveled to Iceland on an official visit and met with Icelandic Prime Minister [[\u00d3lafur Thors]].<ref name=Visits>[http://zion.is/english/photographs1.htm Zion Friends of Israel: Iceland]</ref> In November 1964, Icelandic Prime Minister[[Bjarni Benediktsson (born 1908)|Bjarni Benediktsson]] paid a visit to Israel and met with Israeli Prime Minister [[Levi Eshkol]].<ref name=Visits /> \nIn May 1966, Icelandic President [[Asgeir Asgeirsson]] paid an official visit to Israel and addressed the [[Knesset]].<ref>[https://www.knesset.gov.il/description/eng/doc/speech_asgeirsson_1966_eng.pdf Address by the President of the Republic of Iceland]</ref>\n\nIn September 1992, Israel and the [[European Free Trade Association]] (which includes Iceland) signed a free trade agreement.<ref>[http://www.efta.int/free-trade/free-trade-agreements/israel EFTA: Israel]</ref>\n\n=== Two-state solution ===\nSince the 1990s, Iceland has been a proponent of independence for nations and territories wishing to become independent. The Icelandic government has advocated for a peaceful resolution to the Israeli-Palestinian conflict and has called for international recognition of the State of Palestine.<ref name=MFA>[https://www.mfa.is/media/MFA_pdf/Palestine_Parliamentary_Resolution_Althingi.pdf Proposal for a Parliamentary Resolution On the Recognition of the Independence and Sovereignty of Palestine]</ref> On 30 April 2002 the [[Althing]] (Parliament of Iceland) adopted a Parliamentary Resolution where it was demanded \u201cthat peace negotiations on the establishment of an independent State of Palestine and the security of the State of Israel within internationally recognised borders should begin\u201d.<ref name=MFA /> As a results of this position by the Icelandic government, Israel has expressed its frustration with Iceland.\n\nIn 2010, Iceland expressed its condemnation at the [[United Nations]] against Israel's raid of the [[Gaza flotilla raid|Gaza flotilla]] and Israel's attack on the [[Gaza Strip]].<ref>[https://reliefweb.int/report/occupied-palestinian-territory/human-rights-council-continues-urgent-debate-israeli-raid The Human Rights Council continues urgent debate on Israeli raid on a humanitarian aid flotilla bound for Gaza]</ref> In November 2011, the Althing approved a resolution [[International recognition of the State of Palestine|recognizing an independent and sovereign State of Palestine]] within the pre-1967 [[Six-Day War]] borders becoming the first western European nation to do so.<ref>[https://www.mfa.is/news-and-publications/nr/6509 Parliamentary resolution on an independent and sovereign Palestine]</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/nov/30/iceland-recognises-palestinian-state Iceland recognises Palestinian state]</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, the Icelandic capital of [[Reykjav\u00edk]] voted in favor \"of a general boycott of Israeli goods as long as the occupation of the Palestinian territories continues.\"<ref name=Boycott>[https://www.timesofisrael.com/iceland-capital-retracts-decision-to-boycott-israel/ Iceland capital retracting decision to boycott Israeli goods]</ref> This was criticized by the Icelandic government. Immediately, the Icelandic Ministry of Foreign Affairs declared that the \"decision of Reykjav\u00edk was not in line with Iceland's foreign policy nor does it reflect on Iceland's relations with the State of Israel.\"<ref name=Boycott /> Within a week, Reykjavik mayor Dagur Eggertsson amended the proposal to a boycott of products made in what it deems to be \"occupied\" territory.\n\n=== Controversies ===\nDuring the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2019]], held in [[Tel Aviv]], Icelandic participants [[Hatari (band)|Hatari]] held up scarves with the Palestinian flag on them during the televote.\n\n==State visits==\n'''Presidential and Prime Ministerial visits from Iceland to Israel'''<ref name=Visits />\n\n* Prime Minister [[Bjarni Benediktsson (born 1908)|Bjarni Benediktsson]] (1964)\n* President [[\u00c1sgeir \u00c1sgeirsson]] (1966)\n* Prime Minister [[Dav\u00ed\u00f0 Oddsson]] (1992)\n\n'''Prime Ministerial visits from Israel to Iceland'''<ref name=Visits />\n\n* Prime Minister [[David Ben-Gurion]] (1962)\n\n==Diplomatic missions==\n* Iceland is accredited to Israel directly from the [[Ministry for Foreign Affairs (Iceland)|Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] and maintains an honorary consulate in [[Tel Aviv]].<ref>[https://www.mfa.is/diplomatic-missions/icelandic-missions Icelandic Ministry of Foreign Affairs: Israel]</ref>\n* Israel is accredited to Iceland from its embassy in [[Oslo]], [[Norway]] and maintains an honorary consulate in [[Reykjav\u00edk]].<ref>[http://embassies.gov.il/oslo/Pages/default.aspx Embassy of Israel in Norway]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Dorrit Moussaieff]]\n* [[History of the Jews in Iceland]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Foreign relations of Iceland|Israel}}\n{{Foreign relations of Israel|Iceland}}\n{{Portal bar|Politics|Iceland|Israel}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Iceland-Israel}}\n[[Category:Iceland\u2013Israel relations| ]]\n[[Category:Bilateral relations of Iceland]]\n[[Category:Bilateral relations of Israel]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|1=Diplomatic relations between the Republic of Iceland and the State of Israel}}\n{{Infobox Bilateral relations|Iceland-Israel|Iceland|Israel}}\n\n'''Iceland\u2013Israel relations''' refers to the [[diplomatic relations]] between [[Iceland]] and [[Israel]]. Both nations are members of the [[OECD|Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development]] and the [[World Trade Organization]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:Bjarni Benediktsson and Levi Eshkol 1964.jpg|thumb|right|Israeli Prime Minister [[Levi Eshkol]] greeting Icelandic Prime Minister [[Bjarni Benediktsson (born 1908)|Bjarni Benediktsson]] in [[Jerusalem]], 1964.]]\n\n=== Early relations ===\nOne of the first contacts between Iceland and the people of Israel took place in the 1400s when Icelanders (then part of [[Denmark]]) partook in the [[Crusades]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=6mWY_r7C2VsC&pg=PA165&lpg=PA165&dq=Iceland+crusade+in+holy+land&source=bl&ots=eAVq1Nsu68&sig=8Bpb6CHReiTXaYb6px0li1nEUNM&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjVkYjRnL_YAhUI0