ntary Resolution On the Recognition of the Independence and Sovereignty of Palestine]</ref> On 30 April 2002 the [[Althing]] (Parliament of Iceland) adopted a Parliamentary Resolution where it was demanded \u201cthat peace negotiations on the establishment of an independent State of Palestine and the security of the State of Israel within internationally recognised borders should begin\u201d.<ref name=MFA /> As a results of this position by the Icelandic government, Israel has expressed its frustration with Iceland.\n\nIn 2010, Iceland expressed its condemnation at the [[United Nations]] against Israel's raid of the [[Gaza flotilla raid|Gaza flotilla]] and Israel's attack on the [[Gaza Strip]].<ref>[https://reliefweb.int/report/occupied-palestinian-territory/human-rights-council-continues-urgent-debate-israeli-raid The Human Rights Council continues urgent debate on Israeli raid on a humanitarian aid flotilla bound for Gaza]</ref> In November 2011, the Althing approved a resolution [[International recognition of the State of Palestine|recognizing an independent and sovereign State of Palestine]] within the pre-1967 [[Six-Day War]] borders becoming the first western European nation to do so.<ref>[https://www.mfa.is/news-and-publications/nr/6509 Parliamentary resolution on an independent and sovereign Palestine]</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/nov/30/iceland-recognises-palestinian-state Iceland recognises Palestinian state]</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, the Icelandic capital of [[Reykjav\u00edk]] voted in favor \"of a general boycott of Israeli goods as long as the occupation of the Palestinian territories continues.\"<ref name=Boycott>[https://www.timesofisrael.com/iceland-capital-retracts-decision-to-boycott-israel/ Iceland capital retracting decision to boycott Israeli goods]</ref> This was criticized by the Icelandic government. Immediately, the Icelandic Ministry of Foreign Affairs declared that the \"decision of Reykjav\u00edk was not in line with Iceland's foreign policy nor does it reflect on Iceland's relations with the State of Israel.\"<ref name=Boycott /> Within a week, Reykjavik mayor Dagur Eggertsson amended the proposal to a boycott of products made in what it deems to be \"occupied\" territory.\n\n=== Controversies ===\nDuring the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2019]], held in [[Tel Aviv]], Icelandic participants [[Hatari]] held up scarves with the Palestinian flag on them during the televote.\n\n==State visits==\n'''Presidential and Prime Ministerial visits from Iceland to Israel'''<ref name=Visits />\n\n* Prime Minister [[Bjarni Benediktsson (born 1908)|Bjarni Benediktsson]] (1964)\n* President [[\u00c1sgeir \u00c1sgeirsson]] (1966)\n* Prime Minister [[Dav\u00ed\u00f0 Oddsson]] (1992)\n\n'''Prime Ministerial visits from Israel to Iceland'''<ref name=Visits />\n\n* Prime Minister [[David Ben-Gurion]] (1962)\n\n==Diplomatic missions==\n* Iceland is accredited to Israel directly from the [[Ministry for Foreign Affairs (Iceland)|Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] and maintains an honorary consulate in [[Tel Aviv]].<ref>[https://www.mfa.is/diplomatic-missions/icelandic-missions Icelandic Ministry of Foreign Affairs: Israel]</ref>\n* Israel is accredited to Iceland from its embassy in [[Oslo]], [[Norway]] and maintains an honorary consulate in [[Reykjav\u00edk]].<ref>[http://embassies.gov.il/oslo/Pages/default.aspx Embassy of Israel in Norway]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Dorrit Moussaieff]]\n* [[History of the Jews in Iceland]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Foreign relations of Iceland|Israel}}\n{{Foreign relations of Israel|Iceland}}\n{{Portal bar|Politics|Iceland|Israel}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Iceland-Israel}}\n[[Category:Iceland\u2013Israel relations| ]]\n[[Category:Bilateral relations of Iceland]]\n[[Category:Bilateral relations of Israel]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toHatari(link changed toHatari (band)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.