hinese tariffs and more: 6 new regulations taking effect Jan. 1 Ben Werschkul, Yahoo Finance, December 30, 2019. ]</ref>\n**[[Recreational drug use|Recreational marijuana]] becomes legal in [[Illinois]].<ref>{{cite web|website=Reuters|title=Recreational marijuana becomes legal in Illinois on New Year's Day|date=Dec 24, 2019|author=Brenden O'Brien|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-marijuana-illinois/recreational-marijuana-becomes-legal-in-illinois-on-new-years-day-idUSKBN1YS0US}}</ref>\n* [[January 3]] &ndash; 2019\u201320 Persian Gulf crisis: President [[Donald Trump]] approves the [[2020 Baghdad International Airport airstrike|targeted killing]] of notorious [[Iran]]ian general [[Qasem Soleimani]] and Iraqi paramilitary leader [[Abu Mahdi al-Muhandis]] in [[Baghdad]], Iraq, without the consultation of Congress. Fears of a conflict between Iran and the U.S. results in \"[[World War III]]\" trending on [[Twitter]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.news18.com/news/buzz/twitter-trends-with-world-war-iii-afte-assassination-of-iraqi-commander-in-us-airstrike-2444295.html|title=Twitter Trends with World War III after Assassination of Iraqi Commander in US Airstrike|date=January 3, 2019|work=News18}}</ref>\n* [[January 5]] &ndash; The [[77th Golden Globe Awards]] are held in [[Beverly Hills, California]].<ref>[https://www.cnet.com/news/golden-globes-2020-where-to-watch-date-start-time-and-nominations/ Golden Globes 2020: Where to watch, date, start time and nominations] Jennifer Bisset, Cnet.com, retrieved December 31, 2019</ref>\n* [[January 6]] &ndash; Former film producer [[Harvey Weinstein]] is charged with four additional counts of rape and sexual battery in a [[Los Angeles]] court.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-01-06/harvey-weinstein-criminal-charges-los-angeles-prosecutors|title=On eve of Manhattan sex assault trial, Harvey Weinstein charged with 2013 attacks on women in Los Angeles |date=January 6, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[January 8]]\n**Persian Gulf crisis: Iran [[Operation Martyr Soleimani|launches ballistic missiles]] at Iraqi military bases hosting American troops. More than 60 U.S. service members are eventually treated for [[traumatic brain injury]] by the end of the month,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/01/31/801535693/pentagon-increases-u-s-injury-toll-from-iranian-attack-yet-again-to-64|title=Pentagon Increases U.S. Injury Toll From Iranian Attack Yet Again \u2014 To 64|work=[[NPR]]|date=January 31, 2020|accessdate=February 1, 2020}}</ref> prompting the [[Veterans of Foreign Wars]] organization to demand an apology from the president for apparently downplaying the injuries.<ref>[https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2020/jan/25/donald-trump-asked-to-apologize-by-veterans-group-/ VFW seeks Trump apology for downplaying injuries from Iranian missile strike] By Andrew Blake, The Washington Times, January 25, 2020</ref>\n**The [[American Cancer Society]] reports a 2.2% drop in the [[cancer]] death rate between 2016 and 2017, the largest single-year decline in mortality for this disease ever recorded in the U.S.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pressroom.cancer.org/CancerStats2020|title=Cancer Mortality Continues Steady Decline, Driven by Progress against Lung Cancer|date=January 8, 2020|access-date=January 8, 2020|publisher=American Cancer Society}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Cancer statistics, 2020|date=January 8, 2020|publisher=ACS Journals|doi=10.3322/caac.21590|pmid=31912902|last1=Siegel|first1=Rebecca L.|last2=Miller|first2=Kimberly D.|last3=Jemal|first3=Ahmedin|journal=Ca: A Cancer Journal for Clinicians|volume=70|pages=7\u201330|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n* [[January 9]]\n**Persian Gulf crisis: The [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] votes 224\u2013194 to pass a non-binding [[War Powers Resolution#Iran 2020|War Powers Resolution]] to limit the president's ability to pursue military actions against [[Iran]] without congressional consent.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/house-passes-war-powers-resolution-in-rebuke-of-trumps-actions-against-iran|title=House passes War Powers Resolution in rebuke of Trump's actions against Iran|date=January 9, 2020|work=Fox News}}</ref>\n**The [[United States Department of Justice|Justice Department]] winds down its two-year investigation into [[Hillary Clinton]]'s business dealings after reportedly finding \"nothing of consequence\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/justice-dept-winds-down-clinton-related-inquiry-once-championed-by-trump-it-found-nothing-of-consequence/2020/01/09/ca83932e-32f9-11ea-a053-dc6d944ba776_story.html|title=Justice Dept. winds down Clinton-related inquiry once championed by Trump. It found nothing of consequence.|date=January 9, 2020|access-date=January 10, 2020|work=Washington Post}}</ref>\n* [[January 10]] &ndash; For the first time since the [[Great Recession]], women outnumber men in the American workforce, with women holding 50.04% of all jobs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/women-outnumber-men-us-workforce-jobs-report-first-time-recession-2020-1-1028810054|work=Business Insider|title=Women now outnumber men in the American workforce for the first time since the Great Recession|date=January 10, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[January 11]]\n**Puerto Rico is hit by a 5.9{{M|?}} earthquake and several [[2020 Puerto Rico earthquake|earthquakes]] of 5.0{{M|?}}, following the 7 January 6.4{{M|?}} that left one dead and several wounded in addition to thousands without electric power.<ref>[https://www.nbcnews.com/news/latino/quake-stunned-puerto-rico-hit-another-6-0-magnitude-temblor-n1114021?cid=sm_npd_nn_fb_ma Quake-stunned Puerto Rico hit by another 5.9-magnitude shock] NBC News, January 11, 2020</ref>\n**At least seven people are killed by wind and rain storms across [[Southern United States|the South]].<ref>[https://thehill.com/policy/energy-environment/477842-at-least-7-dead-as-storms-stretch-across-south At least 7 dead as storms stretch across South] BY TAL AXELROD, The Hill, January 11, 2020</ref>\n* [[January 14]]\n**The seventh [[2020 Democratic Party presidential debates|Democratic presidential debate]] is held in [[Des Moines, Iowa]].<ref name=politics>{{citation|website=NBC News|title=The 2019-2020 presidential election calendar: Primaries, debates, caucuses and more|accessdate=Dec 22, 2019|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/2020-presidential-election-events-calendar-n1036266|author=Savannah Smith}}</ref> Six candidates participate.<ref>[https://www.cbsnews.com/live-updates/democratic-debate-who-won-iowa-biden-sanders-warren-buttigieg-steyer-drake-university/ Sanders-Warren tension dominates final debate before Iowa caucuses] CBS News, January 15, 2020</ref>\n**The [[Women's National Basketball Association]] and its players' union reach an eight-year agreement allowing top players to earn $500,000 with an average salary of $130,000. It also provides fully-paid [[Parental leave|maternity leave]].<ref>[https://www.cbsnews.com/news/wnba-salary-cba-new-labor-deal-hikes-average-salary-130000-paid-maternal-leave-today-2019-01-14/ \"Historic\" WNBA labor deal to hike average salary to $130,000, provide paid maternity leave] CBS News, January 14, 2020</ref>\n**[[Delta Air Lines Flight 89]], en route to [[Shanghai]], dumps fuel on a school playground near [[Los Angeles International Airport]]. 60 people, including 17 children, are treated for skin irritation.<ref>[https://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/students-treated-for-skin-irritation-after-apparent-fuel-dump-from-plane-over-school/2290653/ 60 People Treated for Skin Irritation After a Plane Dumps Fuel Over School Near LAX] By Jonathan Lloyd and Patrick Healy, NBC 4 News, January 14, 2020  [https://www.foxnews.com/us/california-elementary-school-students-hurt-plane-apparently-dumps-fuel-playground California elementary school students hurt after plane dumps fuel over playground; more than 50 people treated] By Louis Casiano, Fox News, January 14, 2020</ref>\n* [[January 15]] &ndash; President [[Donald Trump]] and China's Vice Premier [[Liu He (politician)|Liu He]] sign the [[China\u2013United States trade war|U.S.\u2013China Phase One trade deal]] in [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wearden |first1=Graeme |title=US and China sign Phase One trade deal, but experts are sceptical - business live |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/live/2020/jan/15/us-china-trade-deal-trump-tariffs-global-risks-uk-inflation-business-live?page=with:block-5e1f53fe8f0852212f74eabc#block-5e1f53fe8f0852212f74eabc |website=The Guardian |date=January 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Donnan |first1=Shawn |last2=Wingrove |first2=Josh |last3=Mohsin |first3=Saleha |title=U.S. and China Sign Phase One of Trade Deal |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-01-15/u-s-china-sign-phase-one-of-trade-deal-trump-calls-remarkable |website=Bloomberg |date=January 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[January 16]] &ndash; The [[Impeachment trial of Donald Trump|impeachment trial]] of President Donald Trump begins in the [[United States Senate|U.S. Senate]].<ref>{{cite web|website=The Guardian|location=London|title=Trump impeachment trial begins as Schiff reads out charges against president \u2013 live|date=January 16, 2020|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/live/2020/jan/16/trump-impeachment-trial-live-news-ukraine-pelosi-giuliani-latest-updates-senate-democrats|author=Amanda Holpuch}}</ref>\n* [[January 20]] &ndash; 22,000 people attend a [[Right to keep and bear arms in the United States|gun rights]] [[2020 VCDL Lobby Day|rally]] at the [[Virginia State Capitol]] in [[Richmond, Virginia|Richmond]] to protest proposed gun laws.<ref>{{cite web|website=CBS News|title=Thousands of gun-rights activists converge in Virginia's capital to protest proposed gun laws|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/live-updates/richmond-virginia-gun-rally-activists-virginia-capitol-protest-proposed-laws-today-2020-01-20-live-updates/|date=January 20, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[January 21]] &ndash; [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2019\u201320 coronavirus (COVID-19) pandemic]]: The first case of the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19 coronavirus]] [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|in the United States]] is confirmed by the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC).<ref>{{cite web|website=CNN|title=CDC confirms first US case of Wuhan coronavirus|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/01/21/health/wuhan-coronavirus-first-us-case-cdc-bn/index.html|date=Jan 21, 2020|access-date=January 21, 2020}}</ref>\n*[[January 22]] &ndash; The [[History of the Oakland Raiders|Oakland Raiders]] officially relocate to [[Las Vegas]], [[Nevada]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/raiders-officially-say-goodbye-to-oakland-relocate-to-las-vegas-for-2020-and-beyond/|title=Raiders officially say goodbye to Oakland, relocate to Las Vegas for 2020 and beyond|website=CBSSports.com|language=en|access-date=January 27, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[January 24]] &ndash; Donald Trump becomes the first sitting president to personally attend the annual [[March for Life (Washington, D.C.)|March for Life]] anti-abortion protest in Washington, D.C.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/24/politics/trump-march-for-life/index.html|date=January 24, 2020|title=Trump vows support for anti-abortion movement at March for Life rally|work=CNN}}</ref>\n* [[January 26]] &ndash; A [[Death of Kobe Bryant|helicopter crash]] in [[Calabasas, California]] kills nine people, including basketball star [[Kobe Bryant]] and his 13-year-old daughter Gianna Bryant.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28569415/the-nba-world-mourns-death-kobe-bryant|title=NBA, sports worlds mourn the death of Kobe Bryant|date=January 26, 2020|website=[[ESPN]] |access-date=January 26, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[January 29]]\n**President Donald Trump signs the [[United States\u2013Mexico\u2013Canada Agreement]].<ref>{{cite web|website=BBC News|title=Trump signs US Mexico Canada Agreement|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51300625|date=Jan 29, 2020|access-date=January 31, 2020}}</ref>\n**[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|2019\u201320 COVID-19 pandemic]]: President Trump establishes the [[White House Coronavirus Task Force]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/statement-press-secretary-regarding-presidents-coronavirus-task-force/|title=Statement from the Press Secretary Regarding the President's Coronavirus Task Force|website=The White House}}</ref>\n* [[January 30]] &ndash; 2019\u201320 COVID-19 pandemic: The CDC confirms the first case of human-to-human transmission of the COVID-19 coronavirus in the U.S.<ref>{{cite web|website=CNBC|title=CDC confirms first human-to-human transmission of coronavirus in US|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/01/30/cdc-confirms-first-human-to-human-transmission-of-coronavirus-in-us.html|date=Jan 30, 2020|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[January 31]]\n**The U.S. Senate votes 51\u201349 against calling witnesses in President Donald Trump's impeachment trial.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cheney |first1=Kyle |last2=Bresnahan |first2=John |last3=Desiderio |first3=Andrew |date=January 31, 2020 |title=Republicans defeat Democratic bid to hear witnesses in Trump trial |publisher=Politico |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/01/31/murkowski-to-vote-against-calling-witnesses-in-impeachment-trial-109997 |accessdate=February 1, 2020}}</ref>\n**2019\u201320 COVID-19 pandemic: President Trump imposes travel restrictions preventing foreign nationals from entering the U.S. if they visited China within the previous two weeks.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Moritsugu |first1=Ken |last2=Miller |first2=Zeke |title=US bars foreigners coming from China for now over virus fear |url=https://apnews.com/9e22f8aabe2f454593b9f9b4c67eb31f |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |agency=[[Associated Press|AP]] |date=January 31, 2020}}</ref>\n**President Trump expands his [[Trump travel ban|travel ban]] to include six new countries: [[Eritrea]], [[Kyrgyzstan]], [[Myanmar]], [[Nigeria]], [[Sudan]], and [[Tanzania]].<ref>{{cite news |last1= |first1=|title=US travel ban: Trump puts restrictions on six more countries|url= https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51335011|accessdate=February 1, 2020|work=BBC News|date=January 31, 2020}}</ref>\n**At a [[human trafficking]] summit in the [[White House]], Trump creates a new White House position dedicated solely to addressing the issue.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.10tv.com/article/trump-signs-order-creating-post-focused-human-trafficking-2020-jan|title=Trump signs order creating post focused on human trafficking|date=January 31, 2020|accessdate=February 1, 2020|work=10TV WBNS}}</ref>\n\n=== February ===\n\n*[[February 2]] &ndash; [[Super Bowl LIV]]: The [[Kansas City Chiefs]] defeat the [[San Francisco 49ers]], 31&ndash;20.\n*[[February 3]] &ndash; The 2020 [[Iowa]] [[2020 Iowa Democratic caucuses|Democratic]] and [[2020 Iowa Republican caucuses|Republican caucuses]] take place. The Democratic caucus results are delayed due to problems with a [[Shadow Inc.#IowaReporterApp|vote-counting app]].<ref>[https://www.ft.com/content/947aa21c-46ff-11ea-aeb3-955839e06441 Democrats\u2019 Iowa caucus result delayed after count chaos] by Demetri Sevastopulo & Adam Samson, Financial Times, February 5, 2020</ref>\n*[[February 4]] &ndash; President Donald Trump delivers his [[2020 State of the Union Address|third State of the Union]] address. Among the guests are Venezuelan opposition leader [[Juan Guaid\u00f3]] and conservative radio host [[Rush Limbaugh]], who is awarded the [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]].<ref>{{cite web|website=Politico|title=Trump's 2020 State of the Union address|date=Feb 4, 2020|accessdate=February 4, 2020 |url=https://www.politico.com/interactives/2020/trump-state-of-the-union-2020-live-fact-check-transcript-2-4-20/}}</ref>\n*[[February 5]] &ndash; The impeachment trial of President Donald Trump concludes with the Senate voting 52&ndash;48 to [[Impeachment trial of Donald Trump#Verdict|acquit]] on the [[Abuse of power|first article of impeachment]] and 53&ndash;47 on [[Obstruction of Congress|the second charge]]. [[Utah]] Senator [[Mitt Romney]] becomes the first ever senator to vote to remove a president of their own political party.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/05/trump-acquitted-in-impeachment-trial.html|title=Trump acquitted of both charges in Senate impeachment trial|date=February 5, 2020|work=CNBC}}</ref>\n*[[February 6]] &ndash; The [[National Highway Traffic Safety Administration]] (NHTSA) gives permission for [[Nuro|Nuro Inc.]] to deploy up to 5,000 driverless delivery vehicles across the country. It is the first time the NHTSA ever allows deployment of [[automated driving system]]s without meeting all national auto safety standards.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-nuro-autonomous-regulations-idUSKBN20023T|work=Reuters|title=Pizza-toting robots: U.S. lets Nuro deploy driverless delivery vehicles|date=February 6, 2020|accessdate=February 8, 2020}}</ref>\n*[[February 9]] &ndash; The [[92nd Academy Awards]] is held in [[Hollywood]], California.<ref>[https://www.vogue.co.uk/article/oscars Oscars 2020: Everything You Need To Know] BY ALLYSSIA ALLEYNE, Vogue Britain, December 3, 2019</ref> [[Bong Joon-ho]]'s ''[[Parasite (2019 film)|Parasite]]'' becomes the first [[South Korea]]n film to receive Academy Award recognition, as well as the first non-English-language film to win Best Picture.\n*[[February 10]]\n**Persian Gulf crisis: [[The Pentagon]] confirms that more than 100 U.S. troops were diagnosed with [[Traumatic brain injury|traumatic brain injuries]] following the January Iranian ballistic missile attack in Iraq.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-pentagon-tbi-exclusive/exclusive-more-t