>{{cite news |last1=Grimes |first1=William |title=John Prine, Who Chronicled the Human Condition in Song, Dies at 73 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/07/arts/music/john-prine-dead.html |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n<!---{{Commons category|2020 in United States}}--->\n{{Portal|United States|Current events|North America|Politics|Modern history}}\n*[[2020 in United States politics and government]]\n*[[2020 United States presidential election]]\n* [[2020 in politics and government]]\n\n===Country overviews===\n{{Div col}}\n* [[United States]]\n* [[History of United States]]\n* [[History of modern United States]]\n* [[Outline of United States]]\n* [[Government of United States]]\n* [[Politics of United States]]\n* [[Years in United States]]\n* [[Timeline of United States history]]\n{{End div col}}\n\n===Related timelines for current period===\n{{Div col}}\n* [[2020]]\n* [[2020s]]\n*[[2020s in political history]]\n*[[2020s in United States political history]]\n{{End div col}}\n\n===Specific situations and issues===\n{{Div col}}\n* [[2019\u201320 Persian Gulf crisis]]\n* [[Impeachment of Donald Trump]]\n*[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]]\n{{End div col}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category-inline}}\n\n{{Years in the United States}}\n{{Timeline of United States history}}\n{{North America topic|2020 in}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in the United States| ]]\n[[Category:2020s in the United States]]\n[[Category:2020 by country|United States]]\n[[Category:2020 in North America|United States]]\n[[Category:Years of the 21st century in the United States]]\n[[Category:Contemporary history of the United States]]\n", "name_user": "RopeTricks", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eApril", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_in_the_United_States"}
{"title_page": "Ghebrezgiabhier Kibrom", "text_new": "{{short description|Eritrean long distance runner}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name        = Ghebrezgiabhier Kibrom\n| birth_name  = \n| image       =\n| caption     =\n| nationality = Eritrean\n| sport       = Long-distance running\n| event       = Marathon\n| club        = \n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1987|2|1|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| height      =\n| weight      =\n}}\n\n'''Ghebrezgiabhier Kibrom''' (born 1 February 1987) is an Eritrean [[long-distance running|long distance runner]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iaaf.org/athletes/eritrea/ghebrezgiabhier-kibrom-290568 |title=Ghebrezgiabhier Kibrom |publisher=IAAF |accessdate=7 August 2017}}</ref> He came 8th at the 2015 London Marathon and competed in the [[2017 World Championships in Athletics \u2013 Men's marathon|men's marathon]] at the [[2017 World Championships in Athletics]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iaaf.org/competitions/iaaf-world-championships/iaaf-world-championships-london-2017-5151/results/men/marathon/final/startlist#resultheader |title=Marathon men |publisher=IAAF |accessdate=7 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{iaaf name|290568}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kibrom, Ghebrezgiabhier}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Eritrean male long-distance runners]]\n[[Category:Eritrean male marathon runners]]\n[[Category:World Athletics Championships athletes for Eritrea]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n{{Eritrea-athletics-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Eritrean long distance runner}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name        = Ghebrezgiabhier Kibrom\n| birth_name  = \n| image       =\n| caption     =\n| nationality = Eritrean\n| sport       = Long-distance running\n| event       = Marathon\n| club        = \n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1987|2|1|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| height      =\n| weight      =\n}}\n\n'''Ghebrezgiabhier Kibrom''' (born 1 February 1987) is an Eritrean [[long-distance running|long distance runner]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iaaf.org/athletes/eritrea/ghebrezgiabhier-kibrom-290568 |title=Ghebrezgiabhier Kibrom |publisher=IAAF |accessdate=7 August 2017}}</ref> He came 8th at the 2015 London Marathon and competed in the [[2017 World Championships in Athletics \u2013 Men's marathon|men's marathon]] at the [[2017 World Championships in Athletics]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iaaf.org/competitions/iaaf-world-championships/iaaf-world-championships-london-2017-5151/results/men/marathon/final/startlist#resultheader |title=Marathon men |publisher=IAAF |accessdate=7 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{iaaf name|290568}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kibrom, Ghebrezgiabhier}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Eritrean male long-distance runners]]\n[[Category:Eritrean male marathon runners]]\n[[Category:World Athletics Championships athletes for Eritrea]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n{{Eritrea-athletics-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ghebrezgiabhier_Kibrom"}
{"title_page": "Tirutthanigai Saravanaperumal Aiyar", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Tirutthanigai Saravanaperumal Aiyar\n| birth_name  = Saravanaperumal\n| birth_date  = 1799\n| birth_place = \n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = Indian\n| known_for   = Commentary on the [[Tirukkural]] and [[Tiruvalluva Maalai]]\n| occupation  = Tamil scholar\n| father      = Thanigai Kanthappaiyar\n| mother      = \n| spouse      = \n| children    = \n| awards      = \n}}\n\n'''Tirutthanigai Saravanaperumal Aiyar''' (1799\u201319th century CE) was a [[Tamils|Tamil]] scholar, best known for his commentary on the [[Tirukkural]] and other Tamil classics.\n\n==Biography==\nSaravanaperumal Aiyar was the son of great Tamil scholar named Thanigai Kanthappaiyar. The family hailed from [[Thiruthani]] and hence the name \"Thanigai\" became part of the family's names. Kanthappaiyar moved to [[Purasawalkam]] in [[Chennai]]. It is said that Scholar Kachiyappa Sivachariyar wrote ''Vinayakapuranam'' in the Purasawalkam house of Kanthappaiyar. Unlike the title \"Aiyar\" in their names suggest, the Kanthappaiyar family were not [[Brahmins]] but [[Veerashaiva|Veera Saivites]]. Saravanaperumal was the contemporary of [[Ramalinga Swamigal|Ramalinga Vallalar]].<ref name=\"TH_1830Commentary\">{{cite news\n | last = Kolappan \n | first = B.\n | title = 1830 Tirukkural commentary to be relaunched \n | newspaper = The Hindu\n | location = Chennai\n | pages = 4\n | language =\n | publisher = Kasturi & Sons\n | date = 3 October 2019\n | url = https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/1830-tirukkural-commentary-to-be-relaunched/article29578271.ece\n | access-date = 13 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nSaravanaperumal's elder twin brother Vishakaperumal Aiyar too was a renowned Tamil scholar who worked in the Tamil department of the [[Presidency College, Chennai|Presidency College]] in Chennai. His contributions include a poem written as an introduction to his brother's work. He had a collection of many rare books which were later used by [[U. V. Swaminatha Iyer]].<ref name=\"TH_1830Commentary\"/>\n\n==Works==\nSaravanaperumal's greatest work was his detailed commentary on the Tirukkural. This was the first modern commentary to appear in print.{{sfn|Kovaimani and Nagarajan, 2013|pp=116\u2013117}} He published the commentary in 1830 as an adaptation of [[Parimelalhagar]]\u2019s commentary, with word-to-word meaning, brief explanation, and special explanatory text.{{sfn|Kovaimani and Nagarajan, 2013|p=117}} However, the 1830 edition is lost and the oldest available edition was a copy published in 1847. The work came out in several editions (at least eight) until 1928 and became one of the most accepted commentary among academic scholars.{{sfn|Kovaimani and Nagarajan, 2013|p=117}} Many modern commentaries are based on the work of Saravanaperumal Aiyar.<ref name=\"TH_1830Commentary\"/>\n\nSaravanaperumal also wrote the first commentary to the [[Tiruvalluva Maalai]].{{sfn|Desikar, 1969|p=118}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|India|Tamils|Literature|Poetry}}\n* [[Tirukkural]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n{{ref begin}}\n* {{cite book | last = Desikar | first = S. Dhandapani | author-link = | title = \u0ba4\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0bc1\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc1\u0bb1\u0bb3\u0bcd \u0b85\u0bb4\u0b95\u0bc1\u0bae\u0bcd \u0b85\u0bae\u0bc8\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc1\u0bae\u0bcd [Tirukkural: Beauty and Structure] | publisher = Tamil Valarcchi Iyakkam | series =  | volume =  | edition =  | date = 1969 | location = Chennai | pages = | language = Tamil | url = | doi = | id = | isbn = | mr = | zbl = | jfm = | ref={{sfnRef|Desikar, 1969}}}}\n* {{cite book |author= M. G. Kovaimani and P. V. Nagarajan |title= \u0ba4\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0bc1\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc1\u0bb1\u0bb3\u0bcd \u0b86\u0baf\u0bcd\u0bb5\u0bc1\u0bae\u0bbe\u0bb2\u0bc8 [Tirukkural Research Papers] |url= |year= 2013 |edition= 1|publisher=Tamil University | location= Tanjavur |language=Tamil|isbn = 978-81-7090-435-9 |page= |ref={{sfnRef|Kovaimani and Nagarajan, 2013}}}}\n{{ref end}}\n\n{{Tirukkural}}\n{{Tamil language}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tirutthanigai Saravanaperumal Aiyar}}\n[[Category:1799 births]]\n[[Category:Tirukkural commentators]]\n[[Category:Year of death missing]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Tirutthanigai Saravanaperumal Aiyar\n| birth_name  = Saravanaperumal\n| birth_date  = 1799\n| birth_place = \n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = Indian\n| known_for   = Commentary on the [[Tirukkural]] and [[Tiruvalluva Maalai]]\n| occupation  = Tamil scholar\n| father      = Thanigai Kanthappaiyar\n| mother      = \n| spouse      = \n| children    = \n| awards      = \n}}\n\n'''Tirutthanigai Saravanaperumal Aiyar''' (1799\u201319th century CE) was an [[Tamils|Tamil]] scholar, best known for his commentary on the [[Tirukkural]] and other Tamil classics.\n\n==Biography==\nSaravanaperumal Aiyar was the son of great Tamil scholar named Thanigai Kanthappaiyar. The family hailed from [[Thiruthani]] and hence the name \"Thanigai\" became part of the family's names. Kanthappaiyar moved to [[Purasawalkam]] in [[Chennai]]. It is said that Scholar Kachiyappa Sivachariyar wrote ''Vinayakapuranam'' in the Purasawalkam house of Kanthappaiyar. Unlike the title \"Aiyar\" in their names suggest, the Kanthappaiyar family were not [[Brahmins]] but [[Veerashaiva|Veera Saivites]]. Saravanaperumal was the contemporary of [[Ramalinga Swamigal|Ramalinga Vallalar]].<ref name=\"TH_1830Commentary\">{{cite news\n | last = Kolappan \n | first = B.\n | title = 1830 Tirukkural commentary to be relaunched \n | newspaper = The Hindu\n | location = Chennai\n | pages = 4\n | language =\n | publisher = Kasturi & Sons\n | date = 3 October 2019\n | url = https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/1830-tirukkural-commentary-to-be-relaunched/article29578271.ece\n | access-date = 13 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nSaravanaperumal's elder twin brother Vishakaperumal Aiyar too was a renowned Tamil scholar who worked in the Tamil department of the [[Presidency College, Chennai|Presidency College]] in Chennai. His contributions include a poem written as an introduction to his brother's work. He had a collection of many rare books which were later used by [[U. V. Swaminatha Iyer]].<ref name=\"TH_1830Commentary\"/>\n\n==Works==\nSaravanaperumal's greatest work was his detailed commentary on the Tirukkural. This was the first modern commentary to appear in print.{{sfn|Kovaimani and Nagarajan, 2013|pp=116\u2013117}} He published the commentary in 1830 as an adaptation of [[Parimelalhagar]]\u2019s commentary, with word-to-word meaning, brief explanation, and special explanatory text.{{sfn|Kovaimani and Nagarajan, 2013|p=117}} However, the 1830 edition is lost and the oldest available edition was a copy published in 1847. The work came out in several editions (at least eight) until 1928 and became one of the most accepted commentary among academic scholars.{{sfn|Kovaimani and Nagarajan, 2013|p=117}} Many modern commentaries are based on the work of Saravanaperumal Aiyar.<ref name=\"TH_1830Commentary\"/>\n\nSaravanaperumal also wrote the first commentary to the [[Tiruvalluva Maalai]].{{sfn|Desikar, 1969|p=118}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|India|Tamils|Literature|Poetry}}\n* [[Tirukkural]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n{{ref begin}}\n* {{cite book | last = Desikar | first = S. Dhandapani | author-link = | title = \u0ba4\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0bc1\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc1\u0bb1\u0bb3\u0bcd \u0b85\u0bb4\u0b95\u0bc1\u0bae\u0bcd \u0b85\u0bae\u0bc8\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc1\u0bae\u0bcd [Tirukkural: Beauty and Structure] | publisher = Tamil Valarcchi Iyakkam | series =  | volume =  | edition =  | date = 1969 | location = Chennai | pages = | language = Tamil | url = | doi = | id = | isbn = | mr = | zbl = | jfm = | ref={{sfnRef|Desikar, 1969}}}}\n* {{cite book |author= M. G. Kovaimani and P. V. Nagarajan |title= \u0ba4\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0bc1\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc1\u0bb1\u0bb3\u0bcd \u0b86\u0baf\u0bcd\u0bb5\u0bc1\u0bae\u0bbe\u0bb2\u0bc8 [Tirukkural Research Papers] |url= |year= 2013 |edition= 1|publisher=Tamil University | location= Tanjavur |language=Tamil|isbn = 978-81-7090-435-9 |page= |ref={{sfnRef|Kovaimani and Nagarajan, 2013}}}}\n{{ref end}}\n\n{{Tirukkural}}\n{{Tamil language}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tirutthanigai Saravanaperumal Aiyar}}\n[[Category:1799 births]]\n[[Category:Tirukkural commentators]]\n[[Category:Year of death missing]]\n", "name_user": "Tzankra", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor typo fixed.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tirutthanigai_Saravanaperumal_Aiyar"}
{"title_page": "Beovizija", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name      = Beovizija<br>\u0411\u0435\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0437\u0438\u0458\u0430\n| image          = Beovizijalogo.png\n| caption        = \n| creator        = {{flagicon|SRB}} [[Radio Television of Serbia|RTS]]\n| country        = [[Serbia]]\n|language        = [[Serbian language|Serbian]]\n|location = [[Sava Centar]]<br>[[Belgrade]], [[Serbia]] \n| first_aired = 2003\n| last_aired = 2009, 2018 \u2013 present}}\n'''Beovizija''' ({{lang-sr|\u0411\u0435\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0437\u0438\u0458\u0430}}) is a music festival established in 2003. Since 2007 it was the national selection for [[Serbia]]'s representative at the [[Eurovision Song Contest]]. Beovizija is organised and broadcast live each year by [[Radio Television of Serbia|RTS1]], on [[RTRS]] in [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]], and internationally on Eurovision.tv and [[RTS Sat|RTS SAT]] as of 2008. It is held during February and March at [[Belgrade]]'s [[Sava Centar]], and in RTS studios since 2019. The competition started in 2004 and was annually one of the most watched entertainment events in Serbia. In December 2009, RTS announced that it is changing the way it will select its Eurovision competitor and has thus cancelled Beovizija.<ref name=\"\u201eBeovizija ukinuta\">[http://www.blic.rs/Zabava/Vesti/170627/Beovizija-ukinuta \u201eBeovizija\u201c ukinuta] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140106032051/http://www.blic.rs/Zabava/Vesti/170627/Beovizija-ukinuta |date=January 6, 2014 }}</ref> However, on January 19, 2018, RTS confirmed the return of Beovizija as a national selection for the [[Serbia in the Eurovision Song Contest 2018|Serbian]] entry in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2018]]<ref name=\"beovizija_return\">{{cite web|title=RTS |url=https://twitter.com/SerbiaESC/status/954403084524048384|website=Twitter|publisher=Official Twitter account of the RTS|accessdate=19 January 2018}}</ref>, and has been used since.\n\n==History==\n[[Serbia and Montenegro]] were originally due  to enter the Eurovision Song Contest for the first time in 2003 since an 11-year expulsion. The expulsion was brought about the break out of wars in the former [[Yugoslavia]] under which Serbia and Montenegro participated for the last time in 1992.  Unfortunately the EBU stated that too many countries wanted to enter in that year and so some would be forced to withdraw. Serbia and Montenegro (who participated as one country at the time) was one of them.  As a result, [[Serbia and Montenegro]] entered the following year instead.\n\nOriginally the festival was supposed to commence in 2004 and was to be the country's selection for Eurovision however later [[Radio Television of Montenegro]] expressed the wish for a united festival in determining the country's contender at the European event. It was decided that Beovizija would be Serbia's semi final while [[Montevizija]] (held in [[Podgorica]]) would be Montenegro's semi final. The best from the two would compete in a united final show contest under the name [[Evropesma|Evrop(j)esma]].\n[[Image:Beovizija-SC MIR 01-8476734101-2.jpg|thumb|270px|2008 Beovizija stage]]\n[[File:Beovizija.jpg|thumb|right|Beovizija logo used from 2003 to 2009.]]\nThe first Beovizija was held a year before Serbia and Montenegro entered Eurovision and was more of an awards night for the Serbian music industry. In [[Beovizija 2003|2003]] and [[Beovizija 2004|2004]] 28 songs competed while 25 were allowed to compete in [[Beovizija 2005|2005]] and [[Beovizija 2006|2006]]. From 2004 - 2006 there were 8 jury members, from [[Beovizija 2007|2007]] there have been only 3 members of the jury for both the semi-final and final night, while since 2018, 5 jurors vote in every show. In 2004-2006, each juror awarded a set of 12,10,8,7...1 points, with the televote awarding the 9th set of points. From 2007 till today, votes of all jurors are converted into a single set of points, with the televoting awarding another set of points, making it a 50% jury 50% televoting system.\n\nIn 2006 Serbia and Montenegro peacefully split after a referendum. Serbia became an independent country and thus Beovizija became the national selection for the Eurovision Song Contest. The country debuted for the first time independently in 2007. [[Marija \u0160erifovi\u0107]] - Serbia's representative won Eurovision that year.\n\nBeovizija was held over two nights in February. The semi-final consisted of 20 songs. The public's and jury's vote was combined to determine the 10 best songs to proceed to the final. Similarly, the winner of Beovizija was determined. The Serbian music industry awards were handed out on the final night of Beovizija. In 2018, only one show was hosted. Since 2019, Beovizija is held over 3 nights (2 semi finals and a final), with 12 acts performing each night. 6 acts qualify from each semi final, amounting in 12 finalists.\n\nIn 2008 the semi-final were to be held on February 19, 2008 while the final a day later.<ref name=\"rtskonkurs\">[http://ww1.rts.co.rs/euro/jedna_vest.asp?source=komentar&IDNews=626 \u0411\u0435\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0437\u0438\u0458\u0430 2008. &mdash; \u043a\u043e\u043d\u043a\u0443\u0440\u0441 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0443\u0436\u0435\u043d \u0434\u043e 1. \u0434\u0435\u0446\u0435\u043c\u0431\u0440\u0430.]{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} \u0415\u0432\u0440\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0441\u043c\u0430 \u0421\u0440\u0431\u0438\u0458\u0430, \u0420\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043e-\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0437\u0438\u0458\u0430 \u0421\u0440\u0431\u0438\u0458\u0435, 14. \u043d\u043e\u0432\u0435\u043c\u0431\u0430\u0440 2007. Accessed 15.11.2007.</ref> However, due to the declaration of independence on behalf of [[Kosovo]], the festival was delayed until March 9 when the semi-final took place and the finals which took place on March 10.<ref>[http://www.vecernji.hr/newsroom/scena/3016227/index.do Because of the situation in Kosovo, Beovizija delayed until further notice] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080222000000/http://www.vecernji.hr/newsroom/scena/3016227/index.do |date=February 22, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2009, RTS announced that it is changing the way it will select its Eurovision competitor and has thus cancelled Beovizija.<ref name=\"\u201eBeovizija ukinuta\"/>\n\nOn January 19, 2018 RTS officially confirmed the return of Beovizija as a national selection event for the [[Serbia in the Eurovision Song Contest 2018|Serbian]] entry in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2018]]<ref name=\"beovizija_return\" />, and has been used since.\n\n===Host couples===\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\"\n|+ style=\"font-size: bigger;\" | '''Past presenters'''\n! Year !! Name \n|-\n| [[Beovizija 2003|2003]] || Pe\u0111a Stojanovi\u0107<br>Katarina Rebra\u010da<br>Milica Gacin\n|-\n| [[Beovizija 2004|2004]] || Aleksandar Sre\u0107kovi\u0107<br>Ksenija Balaban \n|-\n| [[Beovizija 2005|2005]] || [[Slobodan Ninkovi\u0107|Boda Ninkovi\u0107]]<br>Jelena Jovi\u010di\u0107 \n|-\n| [[Beovizija 2006|2006]] || Boda Ninkovi\u0107<br>Jelena Jovi\u010di\u0107 \n|-\n| [[Beovizija 2007|2007]] || Boda Ninkovi\u0107<br>Jelena Jovi\u010di\u0107\n|-\n| [[Beovizija 2008|2008]] || \u0110or\u0111e Mari\u010di\u0107<br>Branislav Kati\u0107<br>[[Nina Radulovi\u0107]]<br>Kristina Radenkovi\u0107\n|-\n| [[Beovizija 2009|2009]] || [[Jovana Jankovi\u0107]]\n|-\n| [[Beovizija 2018|2018]] || Dragana Kosjerina<br>Kristina Radenkovi\u0107<br>Branko Veselinovi\u0107<br>Aleksandar Stojanovi\u0107\n|-\n| [[Beovizija 2019|2019]] || Dragana Kosjerina<br>Ana Babi\u0107<br>Ivan Mihailovi\u0107<br>Neboj\u0161a Milovanovi\u0107\n|-\n| [[Beovizija 2020|2020]] || Dragana Kosjerina<br>Kristina Radenkovi\u0107<br>Jovan Radomir<br>Stefan Popovi\u0107\n|}\n</center>\n\n==Format==\nThe basic format of the contest since 2004 was that there were approximately twenty singers. Each sing their song once. There is then a ten-minute interval where the viewers are encouraged to SMS and phone in the name of their favourite song. The public vote is incorporated in the special jury's vote. The singer with the most votes wins the contest.\n\nIn 2007 the format of the show changed. Beovizija was held over two nights. On the first night there were twenty singers hoping to go into the final of Beovizija held two days later. Ten singers that had the biggest public vote pass to the finals. At the finals of Beovizija they once again sing their song. There is then a ten-minute interval where the viewers are encouraged to SMS and phone in the name of their favourite song. During the interval, Serbian industry music awards are handed out. The public vote is incorporated in the special jury's vote. The singer with the most votes wins the contest and represents Serbia in the Eurovision Song Contest.\n\nIn 2007, 2008 and 2009 the singers from  [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]], [[Croatia]], the [[Republic of Macedonia]], [[Montenegro]] and [[Slovenia]] that were selected to represent their countries at that year's Eurovision appeared on stage at Beovizija to sing their songs. All performers received a warm welcome from the audience.\n\n==Past Beovizija winners==\n\n<center>\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto\" \n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\"\n|+ style=\"font-size: bigger;\" | '''Past winners'''\n! Year !! Performer !! Song !! Points awarded \n|-\n| [[Beovizija 2003|2003]] || [[To\u0161e Proeski]] || \"\u010cija si\" || /\n|-\n| [[Beovizija 2004|2004]] || [[Negative (pop-rock band)|Negative]] || \"Zbunjena\" || 79 \n|-\n| [[Beovizija 2005|2005]] || [[Jelena Toma\u0161evi\u0107]] || \"Jutro\" || 78\n|-\n| [[Beovizija 2006|2006]] || [[Flamingosi]] featuring [[Ljubi\u0161a Stojanovi\u0107 Louis|Louis]] || \"Ludi letnji ples\" || 94\n|-\n| [[Beovizija 2007|2007]] || [[Marija \u0160erifovi\u0107]] || \"[[Molitva]]\" || 22\n|-\n| [[Beovizija 2008|2008]] || [[Jelena Toma\u0161evi\u0107]] || \"[[Oro (song)|Oro]]\" || 24\n|-\n| [[Beovizija 2009|2009]] || [[Marko Kon]] & [[Milan Nikoli\u0107 (musician)|Milan Nikoli\u0107]] || \"[[Cipela]]\" || 19\n|-\n| [[Beovizija 2018|2018]] || [[Sanja Ili\u0107]] & [[Balkanika]] || \"[[Nova deca]]\"|| 24\n|-\n| [[Beovizija 2019|2019]] || [[Nevena Bo\u017eovi\u0107]] || \"[[Kruna (song)|Kruna]]\" || 20\n|-\n| [[Beovizija 2020|2020]] || [[Hurricane]] || \"[[Hasta la vista (Hurricane song)|Hasta la vista]]\" || 24\n|}\n</center>\n\n==Serbian entries in the Eurovision Song Contest==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n! Year !! Song !! Artist(s) !! Lyricist(s) !! Composer(s) !! Points !! Place\n|- bgcolor=\"silver\"\n| '''[[Eurovision Song Contest 2004|2004]]''' || '''\"[[Lane moje]]\"''' || '''[[\u017deljko Joksimovi\u0107]]''' || Leontina Vukomanovi\u0107 || [[\u017deljko Joksimovi\u0107]] || 263 || '''2nd'''\n|- bgcolor=\"FFD700\"\n| '''[[Eurovision Song Contest 2007|2007]]''' || '''\"[[Molitva]]\"''' || '''[[Marija \u0160erifovi\u0107]]''' || Sa\u0161a Milo\u0161evi\u0107 Mare || [[Vladimir Grai\u0107]] || 268 || '''1st'''  \n|- \n| '''[[Eurovision Song Contest 2008|2008]]''' || '''\"[[Oro (song)|Oro]]\"''' || '''[[Jelena Toma\u0161evi\u0107]]''' || Dejan Ivanovi\u0107 || [[\u017deljko Joksimovi\u0107]] || 160 || '''6th''' \n|- \n| '''[[Eurovision Song Contest 2009|2009]]''' || '''\"[[Cipela]]\"''' || '''[[Marko Kon]] & [[Milan Nikoli\u0107 (musician)|Milan Nikoli\u0107]]''' || [[Aleksandar Kobac]], [[Marko Kon]] || [[Aleksandar Kobac]], [[Marko Kon]], [[Milan Nikoli\u0107 (musician)|Milan Nikoli\u0107]] || 60 (SF) || '''10th''' (SF)\n|-\n| '''[[Eurovision Song Contest 2018|2018]] ||'''\"[[Nova deca|Nova Deca]]\"'''||'''[[Sanja Ili\u0107 & Balkanika]]'''||[[Sanja Ili\u0107|Aleksandar Sanja Ili\u0107]]||[[Sanja Ili\u0107|Aleksandar Sanja Ili\u0107]]|| 113 || '''19th'''\n|-\n| '''[[Eurovision Song Contest 2019|2019]] ||'''\"[[Kruna (song)|Kruna]]\"'''||'''[[Nevena Bo\u017eovi\u0107]]'''||Nevena Bo\u017eovi\u0107||Nevena Bo\u017eovi\u0107|| 89 || '''18th'''\n|-\n|[[Eurovision Song Contest 2020|'''2020''']]\n|'''\"[[Hasta la vista (Hurricane song)|Hasta la vista]]\"'''\n|[[Hurricane (Serbian band)|'''Hurricane''']]\n|Kosana Stoji\u0107, [[Sanja Vu\u010di\u0107]]\n|Nemanja Antoni\u0107\n| colspan=2 {{n/a|Event Cancelled}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}<!--added above External links/Sources by script-assisted edit-->\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Beovizija}}\n*[http://www.rts.rs/ RTS website]\n*[http://www.evropesma.org OGAE Serbia website]\n*[http://www.eurovision.tv Eurovision website]\n\n{{Beovizija}}\n{{Eurovision Song Contest}}\n\n[[Category:Eurovision Song Contest selection events]]\n[[Category:Serbia and Montenegro in the Eurovision Song Contest]]\n[[Category:Serbia in the Eurovision Song Contest]]\n[[Category:Recurring events disestablished in 2009]]\n[[Category:2003 establishments in Serbia]]\n[[Category:Music festivals established in 2003]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name      = Beovizija<br>\u0411\u0435\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0437\u0438\u0458\u0430\n| image          = Beovizijalogo.png\n| caption        = \n| creator        = {{flagicon|SRB}} [[Radio Television of Serbia|RTS]]\n| country        = [[Serbia]]\n|language        = [[Serbian language|Serbian]]\n|location = [[Sava Centar]]<br>[[Belgrade]], [[Serbia]] \n| first_aired = 2003\n| last_aired = 2009, 2018 \u2013 present}}\n'''Beovizija''' ({{lang-sr|\u0411\u0435\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0437\u0438\u0458\u0430}}) is a music festival established in 2003. Since 2007 it was the national selection for [[Serbia]]'s representative at the [[Eurovision Song Contest]]. Beovizija is organised and broadcast live each year by [[Radio Television of Serbia|RTS1]], on [[RTRS]] in [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]], and internationally on Eurovision.tv and [[RTS Sat|RTS SAT]] as of 2008. It is held during February and March at [[Belgrade]]'s [[Sava Centar]], and in RTS studios since 2019. The competition started in 2004 and was annually one of the most watched entertainment events in Serbia. In December 2009, RTS announced that it is changing the way it will select its Eurovision competitor and has thus cancelled Beovizija.<ref name=\"\u201eBeovizija ukinuta\">[http://www.blic.rs/Zabava/Vesti/170627/Beovizija-ukinuta \u201eBeovizija\u201c ukinuta] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140106032051/http://www.blic.rs/Zabava/Vesti/170627/Beovizija-ukinuta |date=January 6, 2014 }}</ref> However, on January 19, 2018, RTS confirmed the return of Beovizija as a national selection for the [[Serbia in the Eurovision Song Contest 2018|Serbian]] entry in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2018]]<ref name=\"beovizija_return\">{{cite web|title=RTS |url=https://twitter.com/SerbiaESC/status/954403084524048384|website=Twitter|publisher=Official Twitter account of the RTS|accessdate=19 January 2018}}</ref>, and has been used since.\n\n==History==\n[[Serbia and Montenegro]] were originally due  to enter the Eurovision Song Contest for the first time in 2003 since an 11-year expulsion. The expulsion was brought about the break out of wars in the former [[Yugoslavia]] under which Serbia and Montenegro participated for the last time in 1992.  Unfortunately the EBU stated that too many countries wanted to enter in that year and so some would be forced to withdraw. Serbia and Montenegro (who participated as one country at the time) was one of them.  As a result, [[Serbia and Montenegro]] entered the following year instead.\n\nOriginally the festival was supposed to commence in 2004 and was to be the country's selection for Eurovision however later [[Radio Television of Montenegro]] expressed the wish for a united festival in determining the country's contender at the European event. It was decided that Beovizija would be Serbia's semi final while [[Montevizija]] (held in [[Podgorica]]) would be Montenegro's semi final. The best from the two would compete in a united final show contest under the name [[Evropesma|Evrop(j)esma]].\n[[Image:Beovizija-SC MIR 01-8476734101-2.jpg|thumb|270px|2008 Beovizija stage]]\n[[File:Beovizija.jpg|thumb|right|Beovizija logo used from 2003 to 2009.]]\nThe first Beovizija was held a year before Serbia and Montenegro entered Eurovision and was more of an awards night for the Serbian music industry. In [[Beovizija 2003|2003]] and [[Beovizija 2004|2004]] 28 songs competed while 25 were allowed to compete in [[Beovizija 2005|2005]] and [[Beovizija 2006|2006]]. From 2004 - 2006 there were 8 jury members, from [[Beovizija 2007|2007]] there have been only 3 members of the jury for both the semi-final and final night, while since 2018, 5 jurors vote in every show. In 2004-2006, each juror awarded a set of 12,10,8,7...1 points, with the televote awarding the 9th set of points. From 2007 till today, votes of all jurors are converted into a single set of points, with the televoting awarding another set of points, making it a 50% jury 50% televoting system.\n\nIn 2006 Serbia and Montenegro peacefully split after a referendum. Serbia became an independent country and thus Beovizija became the national selection for the Eurovision Song Contest. The country debuted for the first time independently in 2007. [[Marija \u0160erifovi\u0107]] - Serbia's representative won Eurovision that year.\n\nBeovizija was held over two nights in February. The semi-final consisted of 20 songs. The public's and jury's vote was combined to determine the 10 best songs to proceed to the final. Similarly, the winner of Beovizija was determined. The Serbian music industry awards were handed out on the final night of Beovizija. In 2018, only one show was hosted. Since 2019, Beovizija is held over 3 nights (2 semi finals and a final), with 12 acts performing each night. 6 acts qualify from each semi final, amounting in 12 finalists.\n\nIn 2008 the semi-final were to be held on February 19, 2008 while the final a day later.<ref name=\"rtskonkurs\">[http://ww1.rts.co.rs/euro/jedna_vest.asp?source=komentar&IDNews=626 \u0411\u0435\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0437\u0438\u0458\u0430 2008. &mdash; \u043a\u043e\u043d\u043a\u0443\u0440\u0441 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0443\u0436\u0435\u043d \u0434\u043e 1. \u0434\u0435\u0446\u0435\u043c\u0431\u0440\u0430.]{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} \u0415\u0432\u0440\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0441\u043c\u0430 \u0421\u0440\u0431\u0438\u0458\u0430, \u0420\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043e-\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0437\u0438\u0458\u0430 \u0421\u0440\u0431\u0438\u0458\u0435, 14. \u043d\u043e\u0432\u0435\u043c\u0431\u0430\u0440 2007. Accessed 15.11.2007.</ref> However, due to the declaration of independence on behalf of [[Kosovo]], the festival was delayed until March 9 when the semi-final took place and the finals which took place on March 10.<ref>[http://www.vecernji.hr/newsroom/scena/3016227/index.do Because of the situation in Kosovo, Beovizija delayed until further notice] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080222000000/http://www.vecernji.hr/newsroom/scena/3016227/index.do |date=February 22, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2009, RTS announced that it is changing the way it will select its Eurovision competitor and has thus cancelled Beovizija.<ref name=\"\u201eBeovizija ukinuta\"/>\n\nOn January 19, 2018 RTS officially confirmed the return of Beovizija as a national selection event for the [[Serbia in the Eurovision Song Contest 2018|Serbian]] entry in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2018]]<ref name=\"beovizija_return\" />, and has been used since.\n\n===Host couples===\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\"\n|+ style=\"font-size: bigger;\" | '''Past presenters'''\n! Year !! Name \n|-\n| [[Beovizija 2003|2003]] || Pe\u0111a Stojanovi\u0107<br>Katarina Rebra\u010da<br>Milica Gacin\n|-\n| [[Beovizija 2004|2004]] || Aleksandar Sre\u0107kovi\u0107<br>Ksenija Balaban \n|-\n| [[Beovizija 2005|2005]] || [[Slobodan Ninkovi\u0107|Boda Ninkovi\u0107]]<br>Jelena Jovi\u010di\u0107 \n|-\n| [[Beovizija 2006|2006]] || Boda Ninkovi\u0107<br>Jelena Jovi\u010di\u0107 \n|-\n| [[Beovizija 2007|2007]] || Boda Ninkovi\u0107<br>Jelena Jovi\u010di\u0107\n|-\n| [[Beovizija 2008|2008]] || \u0110or\u0111e Mari\u010di\u0107<br>Branislav Kati\u0107<br>[[Nina Radulovi\u0107]]<br>Kristina Radenkovi\u0107\n|-\n| [[Beovizija 2009|2009]] || [[Jovana Jankovi\u0107]]\n|-\n| [[Beovizija 2018|2018]] || Dragana Kosjerina<br>Kristina Radenkovi\u0107<br>Branko Veselinovi\u0107<br>Aleksandar Stojanovi\u0107\n|-\n| [[Beovizija 2019|2019]] || Dragana Kosjerina<br>Ana Babi\u0107<br>Ivan Mihailovi\u0107<br>Neboj\u0161a Milovanovi\u0107\n|-\n| [[Beovizija 2020|2020]] || Dragana Kosjerina<br>Kristina Radenkovi\u0107<br>Jovan Radomir<br>Stefan Popovi\u0107\n|}\n</center>\n\n==Format==\nThe basic format of the contest since 2004 was that there were approximately twenty singers. Each sing their song once. There is then a ten-minute interval where the viewers are encouraged to SMS and phone in the name of their favourite song. The public vote is incorporated in the special jury's vote. The singer with the most votes wins the contest.\n\nIn 2007 the format of the show changed. Beovizija was held over two nights. On the first night there were twenty singers hoping to go into the final of Beovizija held two days later. Ten singers that had the biggest public vote pass to the finals. At the finals of Beovizija they once again sing their song. There is then a ten-minute interval where the viewers are encouraged to SMS and phone in the name of their favourite song. During the interval, Serbian industry music awards are handed out. The public vote is incorporated in the special jury's vote. The singer with the most votes wins the contest and represents Serbia in the Eurovision Song Contest.\n\nIn 2007, 2008 and 2009 the singers from  [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]], [[Croatia]], the [[Republic of Macedonia]], [[Montenegro]] and [[Slovenia]] that were selected to represent their countries at that year's Eurovision appeared on stage at Beovizija to sing their songs. All performers received a warm welcome from the audience.\n\n==Past Beovizija winners==\n\n<center>\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto\" \n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\"\n|+ style=\"font-size: bigger;\" | '''Past winners'''\n! Year !! Performer !! Song !! Points awarded \n|-\n| [[Beovizija 2003|2003]] || [[To\u0161e Proeski]] || \"\u010cija si\" || /\n|-\n| [[Beovizija 2004|2004]] || [[Negative (pop-rock band)|Negative]] || \"Zbunjena\" || 79 \n|-\n| [[Beovizija 2005|2005]] || [[Jelena Toma\u0161evi\u0107]] || \"Jutro\" || 78\n|-\n| [[Beovizija 2006|2006]] || [[Flamingosi]] featuring [[Ljubi\u0161a Stojanovi\u0107 Louis|Louis]] || \"Ludi letnji ples\" || 94\n|-\n| [[Beovizija 2007|2007]] || [[Marija \u0160erifovi\u0107]] || \"[[Molitva]]\" || 22\n|-\n| [[Beovizija 2008|2008]] || [[Jelena Toma\u0161evi\u0107]] || \"[[Oro (song)|Oro]]\" || 24\n|-\n| [[Beovizija 2009|2009]] || [[Marko Kon]] & [[Milan Nikoli\u0107 (musician)|Milan Nikoli\u0107]] || \"[[Cipela]]\" || 19\n|-\n| [[Beovizija 2018|2018]] || [[Sanja Ili\u0107]] & [[Balkanika]] || \"[[Nova deca]]\"|| 24\n|-\n| [[Beovizija 2019|2019]] || [[Nevena Bo\u017eovi\u0107]] || \"[[Kruna (song)|Kruna]]\" || 20\n|-\n| [[Beovizija 2020|2020]] || [[Hurricane]] || \"[[Hasta la vista]]\" || 24\n|}\n</center>\n\n==Serbian entries in the Eurovision Song Contest==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n! Year !! Song !! Artist(s) !! Lyricist(s) !! Composer(s) !! Points !! Place\n|- bgcolor=\"silver\"\n| '''[[Eurovision Song Contest 2004|2004]]''' || '''\"[[Lane moje]]\"''' || '''[[\u017deljko Joksimovi\u0107]]''' || Leontina Vukomanovi\u0107 || [[\u017deljko Joksimovi\u0107]] || 263 || '''2nd'''\n|- bgcolor=\"FFD700\"\n| '''[[Eurovision Song Contest 2007|2007]]''' || '''\"[[Molitva]]\"''' || '''[[Marija \u0160erifovi\u0107]]''' || Sa\u0161a Milo\u0161evi\u0107 Mare || [[Vladimir Grai\u0107]] || 268 || '''1st'''  \n|- \n| 